\section{Illustrative Oscillation Spectrum}

To visualize the impact of the spectral-gap correction, we compare the standard oscillation probability with the modified phase including the additional energy-dependent term.

\begin{figure}[h]
\centering

\begin{tikzpicture}

\begin{axis}[
width=12cm,
height=8cm,
xlabel={Neutrino Energy $E$ (GeV)},
ylabel={$P(\nu_\mu \rightarrow \nu_e)$},
xmin=0.5,
xmax=5,
ymin=0,
ymax=1,
legend pos=north east,
grid=both
]

% Standard oscillation curve
\addplot[
blue,
thick,
samples=200,
domain=0.5:5
]
{sin(deg(1.27*2.5e-3*1300/x))^2};

\addlegendentry{Standard Oscillation}

% Modified oscillation curve
\addplot[
red,
thick,
dashed,
samples=200,
domain=0.5:5
]
{sin(deg(1.27*2.5e-3*1300/x + 0.0005*x^3))^2};

\addlegendentry{With Spectral-Gap Correction}

\end{axis}

\end{tikzpicture}

\caption{
Example oscillation probability for a 1300 km baseline, illustrating how a small spectral-gap correction introduces an energy-dependent phase shift. The deviation grows at higher energies due to the $E^3$ scaling of the correction term.
}

\end{figure}
